Instructions for loading accounts into a 6.7 (APOLLO) PIN database. 

This script quickly creates accounts with defined services. You can choose
how many accounts are created, what services are assigned to the accounts
and whether the accounts are credit card or invoice accounts. The services
you can choose are limited to price list and plans loaded into the database.

This script assumes that the pin database has been created and price lists
and plans are known and loaded. You can find out which plans are present
in the database by using select name,descr from plan_t; 

The steps necessary to load multiple accounts using sql_loader are as follows:

- Change directory to .../apps/perf/sql_loader  (this directory)

- Edit ../db_conf.pm
  - set the variables at the top of the file to suit your database
    E.G.
     $CONF_OWNER="pin";
     $CONF_PASSWD="pin";
     $SYS_OWNER="system";
     $SYS_PASSWD="manager";
     $CONF_DBNAME="pindb_some_host";   <-- the database alias in tnsnames.ora

     To test that you have set these value correctly, you should be able to
     type (using the examples above) sqlplus pin/pin@pindb_some_host and
     sqlplus system/manager@pindb_some_host
  
- Edit the mycreate (mycreate.bat on NT)
  - set the $CONF_xxx variables
    $CONF_BEG_ID0     is the starting number for accounts. All accounts created
                      will have a login name of the format userNNNN where NNNN
                      starts at $CONF_BEG_ID0 and increments for each account.
                      You can check the the accounts created by using
                      select login from service_t; (If you have have created
                      many thousands of accounts, use select login from 
                      service_t where rownum < 300; (for example). This will
                      limit the screen output.)
                      
    $CONF_NUM_THREADS This controls how many accounts will be created. The
                      total number of accounts created will be $CONF_NUM_THREADS
                      * number accounts to create per thread (see below)

    @ACCOUNTS structure.
        This is where you specify the accounts services (plan) required, the
        number of accounts to create and the type of account (credit or
        invoice)

        Example :
        @ACCOUNTS= (
                    "'Bench_Basic'" , 40000, 1,"'.'"
                   );
 
         - Bench_Basic (which must be in double and single quotes) is the plan (as
           seen in the NAME field of plan_t
         - 40000 is the number of accounts to create per thread. If the
           $CONF_NUM_THREADS is set to 5 then 200,000 accounts will be
           created. If $CONF_BEG_ID0 is set to 5000, for example, the
           accounts will be created with the LOGIN fields (in service_t) set
           to user5000, user5001 ... user204999.
         - 1 indicates credit card accounts (0 for invoice)
         - The last field is the GL segment

        Example :
        @ACCOUNTS= (
                    "'Basic'" , 40000, 1,"'.'",
                    "'IPT and IP Dial-up'" , 200, 0,"'.'"
                   );

         - The 200,000 Basic accounts will be created as described in the
           above example. NOTE the use of the comma (,) to delimit the
           entries in the structure.
         - 200 * $CONF_NUM_THREADS, 'IPT and IP Dial-up' accounts will also
           be created. These will be invoice accounts. Note that the
           'IPT and IP Dial-up' is and EXACT string match from 
           select name from plan_t;

- Run "perl mycreate" from the command line as user pin

NOTES:

1.	If the number of accounts being created is very big (more than 200000),
	we recommend dropping indexes before running "mycreate". 

1.1     Proceedure to drop the indexes:
        - make sure the database is running 
        - run sqlplus pin/pin@<database alias> @/opt/portal/6.7/sys/dm_oracle/data/drop_indexes.source

        - run mycreate to auto generate accounts (perl mycreate)

1.2     Procedure to re-create the indexes

        When the account creation is complete the indexes should be recreated in
        "unrecoverable parallel" mode (I.E. using the NOLOGGING PARALLEL option)

        To do this, edit the the pin_tables.values file in /opt/portal/6.7/setup/scripts
        and locate the storage definition for the configuration you are using. 
          [  If you dont know what configuration you are using, look in the pin_setup.values file
             in the /opt/portal/6.7/setup directory. There, search for line
                  $MAIN_DB{'storage_model'} = "<some size, Small, Medium, Large>"; 
          ]
 
        Back in the pin_tables.values file, if you are using the Large storage model, 
        for example, the PIN_CONF_STORAGE model to search for is PIN_CONF_STORAGE_HUGE.
        (PIN_CONF_STORAGE_MINI for Small, PIN_CONF_STORAGE_MIDSIZE for Medium.) 
        Locate the eight entries that look like

             "storage (initial NNm next NNNm pctincrease 0 ) ",

        and add the 'nologging parallel' option thus :

             "storage (initial NNm next NNNm pctincrease 0 ) nologging parallel ",

        Repeat for the other entries.

        - cd to /opt/portal/6.7/setup/scripts
        - run  perl pin_crt_idx.pl

        --> if pin_crt_idx.pl does not exist then create the file. The contents of the file
            should read :
              #!/opt/portal/6.7/bin/perl
              #
              # Create Infranet indexes
              # This script must be run as user 'pin' from the /opt/portal/6.7/setup/scripts directory
              #

              require "pin_res.pl";
              require "pin_functions.pl";
              require "pin_oracle_functions.pl";
              require "../pin_setup.values";

              &ExecuteSQL_Statement_From_File( "/opt/portal/6.7/sys/dm_oracle/data/create_indexes.source", 
                                   TRUE, 
                                   TRUE, 
                                   %{%DM_ORACLE->{"db"}} );

1.3     Having recreated the indexes, you may wish to switch logging back on for the
        indexes. To do this efficiently, make a copy of the drop_indexes.source file
        in /opt/portal/6.7/sys/dm_oracle/data (call it logging_indexes.source) and
        replace the 'drop' (at the beginning of each line) with 'alter' and then 
        replace the semi-colon (;) at the end of each line, with 'logging;'

         E.G. drop index i_account__id; will be replaced with
              alter index i_account__id logging;

              In vi, use the commands 16,$ s/^drop/alter/   and  16,$ s/;/ logging;/

        run the script from sql E.G. sqlplus pin/pin@<alias> @logging_indexes.source

       

=========================================================================================================

Using update

 There is possibility to make a portion of DB created by "mycreate" billable by
 Infranet. Perl script "update" is very similar to "mycreate", most of 
 configuration parameters are same and values for them should be same as 
 values in the "mycreate" during creating DB. 

 New for "update" configuration parameter is CONF_PERIODS . Value for this 
 parameter defined what part of DB to bill and actually is a step , how many 
 accounts to skip before billing next account. 
 if CONF_PERIODS=3 "update" will make each third parameter billable. To make 
 parameter billable "update" updates field "actg_next_t" in the table account_t.
 After updating table account_t "update" rebuild index by "actg_next_t".
 Location of the index is given by parameter CONF_TABLESPACE.
 
